                            <td align="center"  height="30" class="bg0"><b>Ido-ani
                              at Christmas</b></td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <td valign="top">
                          <p>Walking down the Marina this morning to my office, i
                            was accosted by a wiff of harmattan haze that got me startled
                            . I stopped and looked around,' harmattan?', I asked myself
                            . As if to confirm it, the green and red Christmas' banner
                            displayed at the entrance of First Bank , Marina, blinked
                            the Christmas' light at me and i winked spontaneously......So
                            Christmas is here ....uhm christmas ! That season of dryness
                            and cracked lips. Then the usual fear came upon me .......the
                            year is caving in .........soon we shall greet each other
                            happy new year! . Slowly, thought of years back started
                            filtering in..... those days at the ido ani.....those
                            Christmas carols ...the crocked jollof rice......last
                            night frolics of 1st term.............folks, those were
                            yuletide! Then I always look forward to raking Christmas
                            bounties from uncles...now my junior folks will ask ,
                            <i>&quot;uncle bunmi ,wetin dey for chrismas now&quot;</i>
                            <br>
                            Those days at ido ani ... I mused, shaking my head, as
                            a mischievous smile merrily warms its way up my contused
                            face. All at once I was flooded with images of those years
                            &#133;..Brisk greetings and flashy acknowledgments, I
                            settled down quickly at my desk and began to knead my
                            laptop's keyboard. Folks let me sing to you the ido-ani
                            old carols!</p>
                          <p>By now , we would have rounded up with the tests and
                            mini exams and it'll be less than three days to get home.
                            Christmas carol will be on Thursday and by Friday it will
                            be over till the following year. Now the atmosphere will
                            be very dry you see students moving in dusty sandals,
                            cracked lips and white faces. Clothes will be spread on
                            that green-turned brown expanse between dining hall and
                            green house. The classroom area suddenly turned desolated
                            - except for few secretive lovers - as students mill around
                            the staff room, dinning hall and the main football field.
                          </p>
                          <p>A walk through the dining hall will see you meeting people
                            like Adelaja, my good friend, Jide Adeladan , Dapo Adegoke,
                            Jasper (my hero from nearby Idogun village) and a school
                            of great Fine-artists (we've got a bunch then, remember
                            ) all under the supervision of the school Fine - Art teachers
                            ; Mr Popoola (archampong.) and Mr Etuk - decorating the
                            dining hall with posters and great nativity picture. </p>
                          <p>The choirs should be some where in the Technology Block
                            putting finishing touches to their voices and acts. The
                            cooks will be busy stirring 'the -much-look forward-to
                            Jolli' (jollof rice). You can't afford not to partake
                            in the festive activities ...for people like me then ..i
                            would have washed my plates ...and made ready to collect
                            plates of rice and fried meats from already made food
                            deals!.(the language then was 'bargain')</p>
                          <p>You wouldn't miss our indefatigable chaplain , Mr OLABODE
                            , at his best, negotiating with all concerned parties
                            to make the event a success. His ubiquitous white Peugeot
                            504; OD something E will be seen running through the school
                            only rivaled by the school bus that shuttles between the
                            school and ido-ani town .</p>
                          <p>Remember the senior all juniors then love...Pateh! Biodun
                            Akinrowo..the incumbent father Christmas ...with his dandy
                            and swaggering gait you would not know his name wasn't
                            <b>santabiodun Akinclaus!</b> Any way he is such a father
                            Christmas in real life for he gives freely and of course
                            takes freely!!!!. I don't know how he gets his paraphernalia.....
                            I used to ask my friend does he bring it to school.</p>
                          <p>7.00pm the bell will ring ...that old rugged behind Red
                            house! and you'll see students in white and purple check
                            trooping out for dinner and the carol. Then, we would
                            have been spent arranging the dinning hall to suit the
                            chapel prefect/social prefect's taste . &quot;whoever
                            designed this U shaped hall did a bad job , does he think
                            of only food!&quot; we will query the unknown contractor
                            , trying to blame someone for our woe of stressful pushing
                            and dragging. You cannot afford not being stained with
                            mould-like dirt of unclean oiled beans and other food
                            remnants. Those wooden benches and tables - receptacles
                            of hot beans and ogbolo soups.<br>
                            To some then, it was more important than the class desks
                            and chairs; to some of us, veteran table soccer d&eacute;tente,
                            we wouldn't forget those tables in a hurry and the pain
                            it caused our fragile finger nails . The tables at the
                            blue house section...near the kitchen..that still retains
                            the veneer and glossy surface were our choice turf. What
                            people like Arewa, Loko, Aderemi , Bolaji Ashiru etc were
                            doing on the football pitch we took solace doing it on
                            a table ! You need to see the way we package individuals'
                            teams and name them after great squads.</p>
                          <p><br>
                            The carol will start , choirs sing and the preacher tells
                            us something about the little infant Jesus.....and father
                            Xmas will just play round dropping gifts here and there.
                          </p>
                          <p>i wouldn't forget this song: </p>
                          <p>Angels from that realms of glory, <br>
                            Wing your flight o'er all the earth<br>
                            Ye who sang creation's story <br>
                            Now proclaim messiah birth ...<br>
                            <i>And the famous chorus follows </i><br>
                            come come and worship ..<br>
                            <b>and those of us at the rear end of the hall will change
                            the chorus to;</b><br>
                            come and come and jegba ( be caned) <br>
                            come and korin(sing)<br>
                            come and so'omo (toast a girl)<br>
                            come and come ...and come and eat&#133;&#133;..!</p>
                          <p>Well folks, all is not about food! The excitement died
                            the moment you are woken up the next morning, then the
                            chapel prefect dilemma starts, chasing home-bound students
                            to rearrange all the tables for the final assembly. Then
                            you will see luxurious buses maneuvering themselves and
                            anxious parent looking for tired wards. Then you know
                            the year is about ending.</p>
                          <p class="fields">Undoubtedly things have changed now, but
                            we can't trade off the experiences and the feelings of
                            those days . we all put our best into such activities
                            and somehow might have been responsible for what ever
                            we have achieved today. Sometimes looking back could elicit
                            pleasure and sometimes pain, but the fun here is remembering
                            it and chuckling. </p>
                          <p>Wishing you a Merry Smiley Christmas.</p>
